                            <comment id="17420128" author="bowen song" created="Sat, 25 Sep 2021 16:55:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I can confirm that I&apos;m experiencing the same issue on a Cassandra 4.0.1 cluster on production. New snapshot is created for those system tables when the server is rebooted or the Cassandra service is restarted. The size of the snapshot is small, but if left untreated, the filesystem may run out of free inodes eventually.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17425071" author="brandon.williams" created="Wed, 6 Oct 2021 16:21:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is caused by &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-15776&quot; title=&quot;python dtest regression caused by CASSANDRA-15637&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-15776&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-15776&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; truncating these tables via CQL, which does not have a mechanism for truncation without snapshotting. I actually couldn&apos;t find a way to truncate without snapshotting, so this patch adds one, uses it instead, and additionally replaces the other two truncateBlocking instances that generate snapshots for prepared statements and available ranges.&lt;/p&gt;


